In this example, the net cash flow is calculated as:

Net Cash Flow=Revenue+Interest Income−Principal Repayment\text{Net Cash Flow} = \text{Revenue} + \text{Interest Income} - \text{Principal Repayment}\text{Net Cash Flow} = \text{Revenue} + \text{Interest Income} - \text{Principal Repayment}

For year 2025:

Net Cash Flow=9,526,500+6,440,000−32,200,000=−16,233,500 EUR\text{Net Cash Flow} = 9,526,500 + 6,440,000 - 32,200,000 = -16,233,500 \, \text{EUR}\text{Net Cash Flow} = 9,526,500 + 6,440,000 - 32,200,000 = -16,233,500 \, \text{EUR}

For year 2044:

Net Cash Flow=9,526,500+322,000−32,200,000=−22,351,500 EUR\text{Net Cash Flow} = 9,526,500 + 322,000 - 32,200,000 = -22,351,500 \, \text{EUR}\text{Net Cash Flow} = 9,526,500 + 322,000 - 32,200,000 = -22,351,500 \, \text{EUR}
This structure results in consistent negative cash flows, which might be manageable if the entity has other revenue streams or if the fund is structured to accommodate these outflows.
Alternatively, the bullet structure could be more suitable if the entity prefers positive cash flows in the early years, with the understanding of a large outflow at maturity.
Regarding the SBLCs, if needed, they can be arranged through Deutsche Bundesbank or other financial institutions, but given the strong backing of the bond, their necessity might be limited.
In conclusion, the choice between bullet and amortizing structures depends on the entity's cash flow preferences and financial strategy. The bullet structure offers positive cash flows for most of the term, while the amortizing structure provides a more gradual repayment but with negative annual cash flows.










Below is a simulation of the cash flow over 20 years for a solar power plant in Germany, financed through a state bond. I will present two scenarios based on your query: the bullet repayment structure (where the principal is repaid at maturity) and the amortizing bond structure (where the principal is repaid gradually). I will also provide an example of necessary Standing Bank Letters of Credit (SBLCs) prioritized through Deutsche Bundesbank, where you hold an account as the set entity for the fund.
Assumptions
Based on the provided data:
Initial Investment (Principal): 644,000,000 EUR
Annual Revenue: 9,526,500 EUR (from the solar power plant)
Interest Rate: -1% per annum (negative yield, meaning bondholders pay interest to the issuer)
Bond Term: 20 years
With a negative interest rate, the issuer (the government or entity) receives interest from the bondholders annually, calculated as 1% of the outstanding principal (the absolute value of -1%).
Bullet Repayment Structure
In the bullet repayment structure, the principal (644,000,000 EUR) is repaid in full at the end of the 20-year term (Year 20). There are no principal repayments during the first 19 years, and the entity receives both revenue and interest annually.
Cash Flow Calculation
Annual Cash Inflows:
Revenue from the solar plant: 9,526,500 EUR
Interest received from bondholders: 644,000,000 EUR × 1% = 6,440,000 EUR
Total inflow (Years 1–19): 9,526,500 + 6,440,000 = 15,966,500 EUR
Annual Cash Outflows:
Years 1–19: 0 EUR (no principal repayment)
Year 20: Principal repayment of 644,000,000 EUR
Net Cash Flow:
Years 1–19: 15,966,500 EUR
Year 20: 15,966,500 - 644,000,000 = -628,033,500 EUR
Cash Flow Table (Bullet Structure)
