Key Insight: The bullet structure provides positive cash flows of 15,966,500 EUR annually for 19 years, followed by a significant negative cash flow in Year 20 due to the principal repayment. This could suit an entity that can manage a large outflow at maturity, perhaps by accumulating reserves or securing additional funding.
Amortizing Bond Structure
In the amortizing bond structure, the principal is repaid gradually over the 20 years in equal annual installments. The interest received each year is based on the outstanding principal at the start of the year.
Cash Flow Calculation
Annual Principal Repayment: 644,000,000 EUR ÷ 20 = 32,200,000 EUR
Outstanding Principal at Start of Year t:
P_t = 644,000,000 - (t - 1) × 32,200,000
Interest Received in Year t:
I_t = P_t × 1%
Net Cash Flow in Year t:
CF_t = Revenue + Interest Received - Principal Repayment
CF_t = 9,526,500 + (P_t × 0.01) - 32,200,000
Example Calculations
Year 1 (2025):
P_1 = 644,000,000 EUR
Interest = 644,000,000 × 0.01 = 6,440,000 EUR
CF_1 = 9,526,500 + 6,440,000 - 32,200,000 = -16,233,500 EUR
Year 2 (2026):
P_2 = 644,000,000 - 32,200,000 = 611,800,000 EUR
Interest = 611,800,000 × 0.01 = 6,118,000 EUR
CF_2 = 9,526,500 + 6,118,000 - 32,200,000 = -16,555,500 EUR
Year 20 (2044):
P_20 = 644,000,000 - 19 × 32,200,000 = 32,200,000 EUR
Interest = 32,200,000 × 0.01 = 322,000 EUR
CF_20 = 9,526,500 + 322,000 - 32,200,000 = -22,351,500 EUR
